The grammar is highly permissive:  

• All 16 non-terminal symbols are reachable from S (via the five alternatives for S and the subsequent recursive rules).  
• Every terminal that appears in the string is produced by at least one reachable non-terminal.  
• There are several left- and right-recursive rules (for example NT4 → NT4 NT0, NT9 → NT6 NT9, NT12 → NT12 NT11, NT15 → NT12 NT15, …) which allow the grammar to concatenate the yields of almost any pair of non-terminals in arbitrary order and length.  
• Base cases for those recursions cover every terminal in the string (e.g. NT5 → 't9', NT13 → 't5', NT12 → 't57', NT14 → 't66', NT15 → 't68', NT0 → 't18', NT14 → 't27', NT8 → 't41', NT12 → 't11', NT1 → 't13', NT2 → 't52', NT3 → 't56', NT15 → 't44', NT9 → 't74', …).  

Because the grammar can freely build larger constituents by repeatedly using the recursive binary rules and then terminate each branch with the appropriate lexical rule, any sequence of terminals that are individually licensed—such as the given 35-token string—can be generated. Therefore the string lies in the language defined by the grammar.

Yes
